1 Data simulation

1.1 Simulation parameters

  • Sample size 10,000 of the whole family-based sample (each family has 2 parents and 3 kids)
    • That means 2,000 is the sample size of pulled samples for OLS, GLS and LMM
  • Number of SNPs 10,000
  • MAF of genotypes 0.3
  • Effect size beta is either
    • 0 under the null hypothesis
    • 0.1 under the null hypothesis

1.2 LMM

LMM architecture

  • Two random effects: genetic and residual.
  • The variance exmplained (that is the heritability in this case) varied among 0.1, 0.3, 0.6 and 0.9

2 Under the null

2.1 Variance of the effect

Observations:

  • The effect variance for OLS is remained constant over different values of var_explained parameter. That what we expected: samples pooled for OLS are independent and have zero genetic variance.
  • The effect variance for LMM depend on var_explained values, but this law is not smooth. We might suspect that the law is related more to the variance-covariance structure that to the values of variance components (sigmas).

4 Explanation of the tendencies

What tendencies have we observed on the previous figures?

  1. The effect variance is the lowest for OLS comparing with GLS and LMM.
  2. The effect variance somehow depend on the heritability or variance explained by genes.

Remeber the formulas:

Study var(y) var(g) var(beta) Approximation Upper Bound
(Pooled) Independent \(\sigma_g^2 I + \sigma_r^2 I = \sigma_r^{*2} I\) \(2pq I\) \(\frac{\hat{\sigma}_r^{*2}}{g_c^T g_c}\) \(\frac{\hat{\sigma}_r^{*2}}{2pq N} \approx \frac{1}{2pq N}\)
Common random effect \(\sigma_f^2 F + \sigma_r^2 I\) \(2pq I\) \(\frac{1}{g_c^T \hat{V}^{-1} g_c}\) \(\frac{1}{2pq \mbox { } trace(\hat{V}^{-1})}\) \(\frac{\hat{\sigma}_g^2 + \hat{\sigma}_r^2}{2pq N} \approx \frac{1}{2pq N}\)
Genetic random effect \(\sigma_g^2 K + \sigma_r^2 I\) \(2pq K\) \(\frac{1}{g_c^T \hat{V}^{-1} g_c}\) \(\frac{1}{2pq \mbox { } trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K)}\) \(\frac{(\sum{\lambda^{-1}_K}/N) \hat{\sigma}_g^2 + \hat{\sigma}_r^2}{2pq N}\)

Notes

  • In the current status of this report, we present experiments only for the situation given on the 1st and 3rd rows of the table.
    • It would be interesting to conduct an experiment for the 2nd row, i.e. “Common random effect”.
    • Results expected for “Common random effect” will be opposite to “Genetic random effect”, as suggest both, derivations in the table above and table in the further section 4.2.

What can we conclude from the table with formulas given above?

  • The factor of relative difference between OLS (row 1) and LMM (both row 2 Common and row 3 Genetic random effect) is equal to the trace value divided by \(N\).

4.1 LMM: genetic random effect

The effect variance estimated by LMM varies with var_explained parameter. See Figures in Sections 2.1 (under the null) and 3.1 (under the alternative).

var_explained trace_transform trace_transform_by_n
0.1 1853.311 0.9266553
0.3 1694.623 0.8473113
0.6 1650.674 0.8253369
0.9 1828.003 0.9140013

4.2 LMM: common variance (family) effect

The figure in Section 3.2.2 from the previous report showed how the effect variance depended on the var_explained parameter.

This dependency is smooth, that can be seen ether on the figure in the previous report or on the table given below.

var_explained trace_transform trace_transform_by_n
0.3 2467.532 1.233766
0.6 4117.647 2.058824
0.9 16086.957 8.043478

4.3 Conclusions

  • Empirically, we observed that the factor trace_transform_by_n is
    • less than 1 for Genetic random effect (that means pooling samples increases the effect variance – a bad thing)
    • greater than 1 for Common random effect (that means pooling samples decreases the effect variance – a good thing)
  • In the Common random effect Scenario, using the upper bound for the exact solution for effect variance, we have shown that pooling samples always decreases the effect variance and improves the power – a good thing.
  • The discrapency between the exact computation of effect variance and its upper bound is increasing when the heritability is increasing.
    • With the heritability is increasing, approximation using the upper bound of the effect variance is getting worse.
